Case Study: ZeuS botnet

Background

ZeuS: A crimeware kit that steals credentials from online services like social networks, online banking accounts, FTP accounts, email accounts and other (phishing)

This blocklist contains all IPv4 addresses associated with ZeuS C&Cswhich are currently being tracked by ZeuS Tracker

Tools we’ll use:

  • Network Intel
  • Graph
  • Some domain knowledge

Network Intel

Feature Engineering in R

It’s often said that “data is the fuel of machine learning.” This isn’t quite true: data is like the crude oil of machine learning which means it has to be refined into features — predictor variables — to be useful for training a model. Without relevant features, you can’t train an accurate model, no matter how complex the machine learning algorithm.

Case Study: Security Incidents

Background: VERIS

The vocabulary for event recording and incident sharing. VERIS is a response to one of the most critical and persistent challenges in the security industry - a lack of quality information. VERIS targets this problem by helping organizations to collect useful incident-related information and to share that information - anonymously and responsibly - with others.

System for Post-Incidents Investigation

Concepts

4 A’s of Incident Details: - Who is behind an incident (Actor)
- Methods uses (Action)
- Devices affected (Asset)
- How they were affected (Attribute)

Aspects of Narrative: - Incident Tracking
- Victim Demographics
- Incident Description
- Discovery & Response
- Impact Assessment

Tools we’ll use:

  • VCDB Community Database
  • verisr2
  • Exploratory Data Analysis tools in R

Flexibility and Form

The design challenge with a “common language” for security incidents are twofold:

  • Structuredness around schema
  • Extensibility (evolving schema)

Flexibility and Form

This resulted in data structures that might be pretty awkward to work with.

Thankfully, we have R.

Demo: JSON directory to CSV

# install devtools 
devtools::install_github("onlyphantom/verisr2")
library(verisr2)
data(vcdb)

To read from a directory containing incidents in JSON, use importveris(".../json_file_path")

Indonesia-related security incidents

id <- involving_country(vcdb, "ID", notes_only=TRUE)
rownames(id) <- NULL
id[,c("summary", "actor.external.notes")]

EDA and Visualization Demo

Works well with other packages from tidyverse():

id <- involving_country(vcdb, "ID")
us <- involving_country(vcdb, "US")
dat <- rbind(id, us)
attacks <- enum2grid(dat, c("action", "asset.variety")) 
class(attacks)
## [1] "gg"     "ggplot"

EDA and Visualization Demo

attacks +
  ggplot2::labs(title="Action vs Asset", subtitle="Indonesia and US, combined") +
  ggplot2::theme(legend.position = "none")
